- No.
Lose to him.

66
00:02:35,659 --> 00:02:37,835
Therapy is a chess match.

67
00:02:37,878 --> 00:02:38,966
And...

68
00:02:39,010 --> 00:02:40,098
I will prevail.

69
00:02:40,141 --> 00:02:42,753
- Or it's about saving
your marriage.

70
00:02:42,796 --> 00:02:44,885
You should make
a grand romantic gesture.

71
00:02:44,929 --> 00:02:46,713
- Ugh, so dumb.
- Seriously?

72
00:02:46,757 --> 00:02:48,367
From the woman who
loves Nancy Meyers movies?

73
00:02:48,411 --> 00:02:49,542
- Yeah.

74
00:02:49,586 --> 00:02:51,022
Here's what
I've learned as a PI.

75
00:02:51,065 --> 00:02:52,763
People suck, everyone cheats,
and love is an illusion.

76
00:02:52,806 --> 00:02:54,678
Nancy Meyers is a fool,
and Holt should start dating.

77
00:02:54,721 --> 00:02:55,853
What?
- You heard me.

78
00:02:55,896 --> 00:02:57,637
It's the only way
you're gonna beat Kevin.

79
00:02:57,681 --> 00:03:00,074
- I'm thinking about it.
I'm considering it,

80
00:03:00,118 --> 00:03:02,729
and I've decided.

81
00:03:02,773 --> 00:03:04,252
I'm in.

82
00:03:04,296 --> 00:03:05,340
- Here it is.

83
00:03:05,384 --> 00:03:06,951
Pappy Boyle's farm.

84
00:03:06,994 --> 00:03:08,953
I spent every summer
here as a kid.

85
00:03:08,996 --> 00:03:10,781
- Got to say, it's
nicer than I was expecting.

86
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:11,999
- Pappy did well
for himself.

87
00:03:12,043 --> 00:03:13,566
He went to
business school in New York.

88
00:03:13,610 --> 00:03:14,959
He got a job
in Wall Street.

89
00:03:15,002 --> 00:03:16,787
And one day his hand
got caught in a subway door.

90
00:03:16,830 --> 00:03:19,050
And he was dragged
from Times Square into Queens.

91
00:03:19,093 --> 00:03:20,399
Largest settlement
in city history.

92
00:03:20,443 --> 00:03:21,748
- Ew.

93
00:03:21,792 --> 00:03:23,837
Pappy should've used
that cash on pest control.

94
00:03:23,881 --> 00:03:25,491
There's giant rats everywhere.

95
00:03:25,535 --> 00:03:27,145
- Those are nutria, Terry.

96
00:03:27,188 --> 00:03:28,146
They're nothing like rats.

97
00:03:28,189 --> 00:03:29,147
They have meatier haunches,

98
00:03:29,190 --> 00:03:30,453
and their teeth
are more orange.

99
00:03:30,496 --> 00:03:32,585
You know, nutria
are actually great pets.

100
00:03:32,629 --> 00:03:33,847
They're affectionate
and smart.

101
00:03:33,891 --> 00:03:35,109
They know how
to open doors.

102
00:03:35,153 --> 00:03:36,023
Plus, you can milk them.

103
00:03:36,067 --> 00:03:37,068
- But...

104
00:03:37,111 --> 00:03:37,895
should you?

105
00:03:37,938 --> 00:03:38,983
- Pappy drank nutria milk,

106
00:03:39,026 --> 00:03:40,071
and he was fit
as a fiddle.

107
00:03:40,114 --> 00:03:41,507
Anyway, you got
to see the house.

108
00:03:41,551 --> 00:03:44,423
I can't wait to show you
the rug I was born on.

109
00:03:44,467 --> 00:03:45,816
- Sure it's been
cleaned since then.

110
00:03:45,859 --> 00:03:47,861
- Charles Boyle,
I love you.

111
00:03:47,905 --> 00:03:50,473
- Sam Boyle,
I love you.

112
00:03:56,522 --> 00:03:57,741
Where's that dead body?

113
00:03:57,784 --> 00:04:00,134
- He's in the barn,
and he looks adorable.

114
00:04:00,178 --> 00:04:01,222
- Ah, terrific.

115
00:04:01,266 --> 00:04:02,267
And everything's set
for the funeral?

116
00:04:02,310 --> 00:04:03,398
- There's one little issue.

117
00:04:03,442 --> 00:04:04,965
We can't find Pappy's will.

118
00:04:05,009 --> 00:04:06,358
- What?
- He wanted to leave the farm

119
00:04:06,401 --> 00:04:07,490
to the Council of Cousins,

120
00:04:07,533 --> 00:04:08,534
but if we don't
find those papers,

121
00:04:08,578 --> 00:04:09,883
it goes to Cousin Lyndon.

122
00:04:09,927 --> 00:04:11,015
- Oh, no.

123
00:04:11,058 --> 00:04:12,625
- Who's Cousin Lyndon?
- Pappy's son.

124
00:04:12,669 --> 00:04:13,844
He's the black sheep
of the family.

125
00:04:13,887 --> 00:04:15,802
- Wait, so we have
a wealthy patriarch

126
00:04:15,846 --> 00:04:17,891
who mysteriously died,
a missing will,

127
00:04:17,935 --> 00:04:20,241
and a black sheep set
to inherit everything?

128
00:04:20,285 --> 00:04:21,939
Am I the only one
who suspects foul play here?

129
00:04:21,982 --> 00:04:24,637
- He didn't die mysteriously.
He was 93.

130
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:25,812
- He was fit as fiddle, Terr.

131
00:04:25,856 --> 00:04:27,292
From all the nutria milk.

132
00:04:27,335 --> 00:04:28,380
- Don't be ridiculous.

133
00:04:28,423 --> 00:04:29,686
No Boyle would
ever commit murder.

134
00:04:29,729 --> 00:04:31,339
Boyles don't even
get mad at each other.

135
00:04:31,383 --> 00:04:34,212
Except in that rare instance
of cousin-on-cousin jealousy.

136
00:04:34,255 --> 00:04:35,822
- You're just bored
from your suspension

137
00:04:35,866 --> 00:04:37,258
and desperate
to find a case to work.

138
00:04:37,302 --> 00:04:38,651
- No.
That's not it.

139
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:39,826
I'm just telling you,

140
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:41,698
something doesn't
smell right here.

141
00:04:41,741 --> 00:04:43,177
- Oh, yeah.
That's Pappy's body.

142
00:04:43,221 --> 00:04:44,875
Cousin Mel did
the embalming in here,

143
00:04:44,918 --> 00:04:47,225
and I think she forgot
to add something.

144
00:04:47,268 --> 00:04:48,356
- Well...

145
00:04:48,400 --> 00:04:50,271
that's a disturbing revelation.

146
00:04:51,882 --> 00:04:53,579
- Hey.
What's going on?

147
00:04:53,623 --> 00:04:54,841
- I'm helping Holt
pick a dating site.

148
00:04:54,885 --> 00:04:56,147
- Oh, this looks good.

149
00:04:56,190 --> 00:04:57,409
- PhDs only.

150
00:04:57,452 --> 00:04:58,715
- Uh, actually
in this context,

151
00:04:58,758 --> 00:05:00,978
PHD stands for
Pretty Huge

152
00:05:01,021 --> 00:05:02,588
- Oh, my.

153
00:05:02,632 --> 00:05:05,025
I can only assume that MDs only
stands for Medium

154
00:05:05,069 --> 00:05:06,418
- Rosa, can I talk
to you for a second?

155
00:05:06,461 --> 00:05:07,854
What the hell are you doing?

156
00:05:07,898 --> 00:05:10,030
Why are you trying to get Holt
and Kevin to break up?

157
00:05:10,074 --> 00:05:11,771
- I'm trying to get Holt
and Kevin back together.

158
00:05:11,815 --> 00:05:13,556
He and Kevin are perfect
for each other.

159
00:05:13,599 --> 00:05:14,818
He just needs
to realize that.

160
00:05:14,861 --> 00:05:16,341
Once he sees what other
trash is out there,

161
00:05:16,384 --> 00:05:18,561
he's gonna go running straight
back into Kevin's arms,

162
00:05:18,604 --> 00:05:20,214
just like
in a Nancy Meyers movie.

163
00:05:20,258 --> 00:05:21,651
- So you still love
Nancy Meyers?

164
00:05:21,694 --> 00:05:23,391
- I will never turn my back
on Nancy Meyers.

165
00:05:23,435 --> 00:05:24,784
- Okay.
I'm in.

166
00:05:24,828 --> 00:05:27,613
Let operation
"Lucky Number Kevin" begin.

167
00:05:27,657 --> 00:05:28,614
- I'm out.
- No, no, no.

168
00:05:28,658 --> 00:05:29,963
We don't have
to call it that.

169
00:05:30,007 --> 00:05:31,965
- Okay, then I'll think
I'll finish up by saying

170
00:05:32,009 --> 00:05:34,228
Pappy Boyle
was the best hugger.

171
00:05:34,272 --> 00:05:36,579
Which is surprising because
he lost his hand in the subway.

172
00:05:36,622 --> 00:05:40,452
But he always said,
"You don't hug with your hands,

173
00:05:40,495 --> 00:05:42,323
"you hug with your heart.

174
00:05:42,367 --> 00:05:44,674
And your groin."
He got that groin involved.

175
00:05:44,717 --> 00:05:47,154
- Uh, a lot of groin talk
for a eulogy.

176
00:05:47,198 --> 00:05:48,503
- Everyone,

177
00:05:48,547 --> 00:05:50,418
there's something you need
to see in the barn.

178
00:05:50,462 --> 00:05:51,681
The game...

179
00:05:51,724 --> 00:05:52,899
is afoot.

180
00:05:52,943 --> 00:05:54,901
- Pappy Boyle was 93.

181
00:05:54,945 --> 00:05:56,511
Who would've suspected
that his death stemmed

182
00:05:56,555 --> 00:05:59,036
from anything other than the
cruel embrace of Father Time?

183
00:05:59,079 --> 00:06:01,212
To suggest as much
might get someone labeled

184
00:06:01,255 --> 00:06:02,517
a crackpot, a kook,

185
00:06:02,561 --> 00:06:04,694
someone that's
"bored with their suspension."

186
00:06:04,737 --> 00:06:06,478
- Can you cut the
"Harriet The Spy" windup?

187
00:06:06,521 --> 00:06:07,958
It stinks in here.

188
00:06:08,001 --> 00:06:10,569
- What you're smelling, Terry,
is duplicity and deceit.

189
00:06:10,613 --> 00:06:12,179
- I think it's
actually Pappy's organs.

190
00:06:12,223 --> 00:06:13,746
- Sam, you're kind of messing
with my flow right now.

191
00:06:13,790 --> 00:06:15,748
Point is, I was examining
the body,

192
00:06:15,792 --> 00:06:17,837
and I found something.

193
00:06:17,881 --> 00:06:21,014
Classic ulceration
and desquamation of the mouth.

194
00:06:21,058 --> 00:06:23,451
Telltale signs
of poisoning.

195
00:06:24,539 --> 00:06:25,976
- In other words...

196
00:06:26,019 --> 00:06:28,587
What we have ourselves here

197
00:06:28,631 --> 00:06:31,851
is a good
ol' fashioned murder...

198
00:06:31,895 --> 00:06:33,723
- Oh, no.

199
00:06:33,766 --> 00:06:35,202
- Of a man
who you all loved dearly.

200
00:06:35,246 --> 00:06:36,421
I shouldn't have done
the "Knives Out" accent.

201
00:06:39,293 --> 00:06:40,860
- All right.
A man has been poisoned,

202
00:06:40,904 --> 00:06:42,296
his will is missing,

203
00:06:42,340 --> 00:06:43,254
and there's only one person
who stands to profit.

204
00:06:43,297 --> 00:06:44,429
Lyndon Boyle.

205
00:06:44,472 --> 00:06:45,865
- Lyndon's not a killer.

206
00:06:45,909 --> 00:06:47,650
- I mean, he did skip a Boyle
family Zoom last summer.

207
00:06:47,693 --> 00:06:48,694
- Yeah, it's true.

208
00:06:48,738 --> 00:06:49,869
It's seven hours out
of your day.

209
00:06:49,913 --> 00:06:51,175
How hard is that to fit in?

210
00:06:51,218 --> 00:06:53,394
- Okay, let's set up
an interrogation room.

211
00:06:53,438 --> 00:06:55,962
I wanna make this guy as
uncomfortable as possible.

212
00:06:57,703 --> 00:06:58,965
I thought we were going
for uncomfortable.

213
00:06:59,009 --> 00:07:00,271
What's with the rocking chair?

214
00:07:00,314 --> 00:07:02,142
- It's a farm.
All the chairs are rockers.

215
00:07:02,186 --> 00:07:04,449
But don't worry,
I under-steeped the tea.

216
00:07:04,492 --> 00:07:06,712
- Ugh.
It's so weak.

217
00:07:06,756 --> 00:07:08,279
Why am I being treated
like a criminal?

218
00:07:08,322 --> 00:07:09,497
- Okay.
I stand corrected.

219
00:07:09,541 --> 00:07:11,456
We'd like to ask you
a few questions.

220
00:07:11,499 --> 00:07:13,545
Tell us about your last contact
with your father.

221
00:07:13,588 --> 00:07:14,720
- Pappy?

222
00:07:14,764 --> 00:07:15,721
Well, I saw him
at his birthday party.

223
00:07:15,765 --> 00:07:16,940
- Mm-hmm.
And was there anything

224
00:07:16,983 --> 00:07:17,941
unusual about that night?

225
00:07:17,984 --> 00:07:19,116
- Nothing unusual at all.

226
00:07:19,159 --> 00:07:20,770
We ate a pig
from snout to anus,

227
00:07:20,813 --> 00:07:23,250
and then took turns giving
each other head massages.

228
00:07:23,294 --> 00:07:25,296
I was tired.
So I found Pappy,

229
00:07:25,339 --> 00:07:26,558
wished him a happy birthday.

230
00:07:26,601 --> 00:07:28,212
We hugged
for six minutes.

231
00:07:28,255 --> 00:07:29,953
It was the last time
I saw him alive.

232
00:07:32,042 --> 00:07:33,130
- Did you see those tears?

233
00:07:33,173 --> 00:07:34,131
No way he did it.

234
00:07:34,174 --> 00:07:35,175
- Are you serious?

235
00:07:35,219 --> 00:07:36,524
Anyone can fake cry.

236
00:07:36,568 --> 00:07:38,004
You just have
to think of something sad.

237
00:07:38,048 --> 00:07:39,963
Like that episode of
"Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles"

238
00:07:40,006 --> 00:07:41,007
when Leonardo was in a coma.

239
00:07:41,051 --> 00:07:41,965
- And that works?

240
00:07:42,008 --> 00:07:43,009
- Yeah.

241
00:07:43,053 --> 00:07:44,358
Yeah, it does.

242
00:07:44,402 --> 00:07:45,664
Now, come on.

243
00:07:45,708 --> 00:07:47,187
Let's go poke some holes
in Lyndon's story.

244
00:07:47,231 --> 00:07:50,451
- It was such a great party.
Everyone had the best time.

245
00:07:50,495 --> 00:07:51,496
I mean, except for Lyndon.

246
00:07:51,539 --> 00:07:52,497
- Lyndon wasn't happy?

247
00:07:52,540 --> 00:07:53,759
- Yeah, it was strange.

248
00:07:53,803 --> 00:07:55,369
He was passing
through the living room.

249
00:07:55,413 --> 00:07:57,545
I asked him
if he wanted a little HJ.

250
00:07:57,589 --> 00:07:58,895
But he just ignored me.

251
00:07:58,938 --> 00:08:01,201
I mean, who doesn't want
an HJ from their cousin?

252
00:08:01,245 --> 00:08:02,550
- Hold up.
